Running a business as an introverted creative who is very private should not be complicated, yet it often is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with the big (and devilish) tech companies using extrovert techniques. Promote yourself here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service checked, be available 24/7, seven days a week, answer questions with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
01/03/2024
It is a year of transition for me.
I don't want to feed the big tech companies with my money, my data, and my energy. Nor do I want coaches who have only one extrovert solution to apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my business while fighting against the idea I've long believed in, that you have to do things a certain way to succeed.
Wish me good luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday, and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to a CRM based in Europe for better compliance with the GDPR, and I will be transferring my business over the next few weeks.
I have transferred my MX to Proton and I am now fully benefiting from SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
03/03/2024
